Cardio Good Fitness Project¶

My Objective¶

As a data scientist, my goal for this project will be to develop a detailed customer profile for each of the different products offered by Cardio Good Fitness. I will utilize the data at hand to extrapolate possible trends or patterns for the customers of each different product. Based on my findings, I will determine all possible insights that will help me better understand the data at large. Using the insights and understanding gained from my analysis, I will make my recomendations to the business about how they may be able to reach new customers.

Data Dictionary¶

The data is about customers of the treadmill product(s) of a retail store called Cardio Good Fitness. It contains the following variables-

  1. Product - The model no. of the treadmill
  2. Age - Age of the customer in no of years
  3. Gender - Gender of the customer
  4. Education - Education of the customer in no. of years
  5. Marital Status - Marital status of the customer
  6. Usage - Avg. # times the customer wants to use the treadmill every week
  7. Fitness - Self rated fitness score of the customer (5 - very fit, 1 - very unfit)
  8. Income - Income of the customer
  9. Miles- Miles that a customer expects to run

  • It looks like the strongest correlation is between Fitness and Miles at 0.79

  • Education seems to have some correlation with income at 0.63

These correlations make sense as the customer's sense of their self fitness rating, expected usage, and expected miles, should be in line with each other. People would generally have a good sense of their exercise levels and goals which would compare relatively across all 3 of these categories.

  • Education and Income being correlated is a typical expectation to see in general, so there is no surprise that they have some correlation amongst the our customer data

The others being at close to 0.5 or less aren't showing very strong correlations with each other. There is still some observations we can take from these lower correlations.

  • Age seems to have very little correlation with any of the other categories. It has the lowest correlations with all of them except for some with income at 0.51.

Outlier Treatment¶

  • It's good to take a look at the outliers in your data all together in order to make sure they make sense or see if any of our columns may need to be treated.
In [45]:
# boxplots are one of the best ways to visually see your outliers side by side
# for this to work we need to put all the numeric columns in to a list
numeric_cols = ['Age', 'Education', 'Usage', 'Fitness', 'Income', 'Miles']
plt.figure(figsize=(18,12))

for i, variable in enumerate(numeric_cols):
  plt.subplot(3,3, i+1)
  plt.boxplot(df[variable], whis=1.5)
  plt.tight_layout
  plt.title(variable)

plt.show()

It looks like we have at least 1 outlier in every column and some with quite a few such as Income and Miles.

  • With Age there will always be a wider range of customers interested in fitness so we wouldn't want to treat these and lose information important to customer profiles. We can potentially better see which products attract which age range to better advertise each product accordingly.
  • Education is also expected to have a range with customers, and knowing where are customers are at in education level could be helpful in product marketing as well.
  • Income has a lot of outliers, but since we want to establish customer profiles for each product, knowing which product attracts higher income customers is very valuable information and we would not want to drop these outliers.
  • Usage, Fitness, and Miles are all customer reported information based on their assessments and expectations. This gives us valuable insight into how the customers of each product view themselves in relation to fitness level and what they expect to get out of their product. This is essentially our user feedback and there will always be a wide range in answers as everyone will view their situation differently. The trends we see develop through their self reported answers are just as much, if not more, insightful than any of the other static demographic information.

Based on my analysis of our categories, we do need to do any outlier treatment, because in the broader scope of customer base and product profiles all of these outliers constitute valuable information that should not be dropped.

Conclusive Insights¶

I have put together what I see as a picture of customer profiles for each product based on trends seen in this dataset.

Product TM195¶

  • TH195 is fairly distributed throughout age ranges, but your target demographic would be ages 23-28, with 23 being the majority age for this product.
  • Gender is evenly split
  • Primarily customers have 14 or 16 years of education with more having 16 years
  • There were more partnered customers than single, but this was the overall trend for the dataset so I wouldn't put too much weight behind this statistic
  • Customers of TM195 said they would like to use the product 2-4 times a week with 3 being the highest response.
  • While this product's overall customer income ranged from roughly 29,000 to 68,000, this was the only product sold under about 31,500. The largest customer segment though was in the 35,000 to 55,000 range
  • On a scale of 1-5 most customers rated themselves a 3 so mostly moderately fit people are using this product.
  • while there was a large range on customer expectations for miles, the majority of customers fell between 47-113 miles. This shows both casual and more serious runners use this product.

Product TM498¶

  • The primary target age range should be 23-25 with 25 being the highest, and there was also some smaller increased customer use at 31-35 but not near as much. Still a good secondary target age for increased customers.
  • Gender split nearly even
  • Customer education primarily at 14 and 16 years, with 16 being the highest.
  • Customers expect to use it 2-4 times a week with 3 being highest
  • Fitness level 3 overall highest, but an interesting thing was that users of this product were the only ones to not have any rate themselves a 5.
  • Income ranges from 33,000 to 63,000 with the target range being 43,000 to 53,000 for the majority of customers.
  • 42 - 127 miles were the larger portion of customer answers so you also have casual to serious fitness customers for this product.

Producut TM798¶

  • Target age of 22-30 for largest customer segment with 24-25 being the highest part.
  • Significantly higher Male customer base
  • education 16 and 18 years with 18 years being the highest amongst customers. Also of note, TM798 was the only product sold to any customer beyond 18 years of education.
  • Customer response was 4 to 7 times a week for usage with 4 being the highest answer, but TM798 was the only product with customers saying they would use it 6 or 7 times a week
  • The majority of TM798 customers reported their fitness level as a 5
  • While incomes ranged from 48,000 to 105,000, TM798 was the only product sold to customers with incomes higher than 70,000 and the higher number of customers for this product were in the 90,000 range. While this product may have some customers with income as low as 48,000, This is definitely the sole product choice of those with the higher incomes.
  • Customer Miles were also reported higher for TM798 at the main interval being between 100-200 miles there were even customers responding with 240-360 miles. No other products had customer responses near that high.

Recommendations for reaching new customers¶

Based on my findings Cardio Good Fitness could look into some of the followings suggestions as to new target markets for each of their products.

  • Product TM 195 already has a unique position in one portion of the customer income base. This product is the only one reaching customers with below roughly 31,500 in income. It is not very many customers though and, while also smaller, TM195 still has more customers in 12-13 years of education than others. The above research shows that there is some correlation between income level and education which seems to reflect here. So since there is already a small footing in the door with this market segment, it would be an open and already somewhat introduced market with great possibilities. It would also help drive TM195 sales into a more differentiated market position, because right now TM195 and TM498 seem to share a lot of the same demographic. Making this shift would help to stop TM195 and TM498 from cannibalizing each other's market share.

  • Product TM498 has the highest number of customers from the 23 to 25 age range, but there is a smaller, yet noticeable, uptick in customers for the 31-35 age range. This is one area where TM498 shows some different customer interest. Another interesting fact was that no customers of TM498 rated themselves a 5 on their self fitness scores when the other products both had some. These are two of the more unique differences I was able to see for TM498 because otherwise it is fairly similar to product TM195 with regard to the main age level, gender split, education, and usage. So perhaps marketing to those ages 31-35 and marketing it as a product for those not 5 out of 5 in their fitness confidence already, but as the product to get them there. This is a position where there is some difference from product TM195 and they should look into expanding into this customer segment in order to help with the overlap in customers between products TM498 and TM195

  • Product TM798 is the clear stand out for being a different product. It is the elite model for those with a higher level of education, a higher income, those who consider themselves mostly 5 out 5 fit already and will use this product 6 to 7 times a week to run more than 240 miles. Now these are all examples of where it differentiates from the other two products, but it does have a wider range of customers for all of these categories not just the top percent. So while this product seems to already know its customer base and be reaching its own market segment, that is entirely different from the other two products, the one big area where they are lagging behind is in gender. The other two products seem to do equally well with both men and women, but TM798 has a highly male dominated consumer base. Product TM798 needs to stay at its high level status appeal but find a way to reach more women in order to close the gender gap as the other two products have done.

Examples
--------

    The simplest way to use nbconvert is

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb

            which will convert mynotebook.ipynb to the default format (probably HTML).

            You can specify the export format with `--to`.
            Options include ['asciidoc', 'custom', 'html', 'latex', 'markdown', 'notebook', 'pdf', 'python', 'rst', 'script', 'slides'].

            > jupyter nbconvert --to latex mynotebook.ipynb

            Both HTML and LaTeX support multiple output templates. LaTeX includes
            'base', 'article' and 'report'.  HTML includes 'basic' and 'full'. You
            can specify the flavor of the format used.

            > jupyter nbconvert --to html --template basic mynotebook.ipynb

            You can also pipe the output to stdout, rather than a file

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --stdout

            PDF is generated via latex

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to pdf

            You can get (and serve) a Reveal.js-powered slideshow

            > jupyter nbconvert myslides.ipynb --to slides --post serve

            Multiple notebooks can be given at the command line in a couple of 
            different ways:

            > jupyter nbconvert notebook*.ipynb
            > jupyter nbconvert notebook1.ipynb notebook2.ipynb

            or you can specify the notebooks list in a config file, containing::

                c.NbConvertApp.notebooks = ["my_notebook.ipynb"]

            > jupyter nbconvert --config mycfg.py

To see all available configurables, use `--help-all`.
